00:00:04.850 --> 00:00:06.450
- All right, good
evening, everyone.

00:00:06.450 --> 00:00:07.850
My name's Anthony Brooks.

00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:10.170
I do political
reporting with WBUR.

00:00:10.170 --> 00:00:12.050
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:12.050 --> 00:00:12.950
Thank you.

00:00:12.950 --> 00:00:14.210
Thank you for that.

00:00:14.210 --> 00:00:16.434
Thank you for
coming out tonight.

00:00:16.434 --> 00:00:18.350
I know this is going to
be a great discussion.

00:00:18.350 --> 00:00:21.410
My job is to
introduce the panel,

00:00:21.410 --> 00:00:23.810
but first I want to
acknowledge Radcliffe

00:00:23.810 --> 00:00:28.220
for hosting this event and say
a couple of things about that.

00:00:28.220 --> 00:00:31.970
So we're meeting in a
really fitting location.

00:00:31.970 --> 00:00:35.240
This is, as many of you probably
know, the former Radcliffe

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:38.690
College gymnasium, where
generations of female athletes

00:00:38.690 --> 00:00:41.780
played basketball, hung from
ropes from those rafters,

00:00:41.780 --> 00:00:43.610
ran around that track.

00:00:43.610 --> 00:00:47.630
And today, the building
is the Knafel Center,

00:00:47.630 --> 00:00:51.050
which is the central meeting
place of the Radcliffe

00:00:51.050 --> 00:00:52.970
Institute for Advanced Study.

00:00:52.970 --> 00:00:55.610
And the Radcliffe Institute
is Harvard's Institute

00:00:55.610 --> 00:00:59.630
for Advanced Study dedicated
to sharing transformative ideas

00:00:59.630 --> 00:01:01.850
across all disciplines.

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:05.480
Tonight's event is part
of a two year initiative

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:09.110
that the Institute is
pursuing about citizenship

00:01:09.110 --> 00:01:12.860
in anticipation of the 100th
anniversary of the ratification

00:01:12.860 --> 00:01:15.350
of the 19th Amendment.

00:01:15.350 --> 00:01:18.540
That's the one that gave
women the right to vote,

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:20.125
so it's an important one.

00:01:20.125 --> 00:01:25.830
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:25.830 --> 00:01:27.450
One little housekeeping note.

00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:30.540
This program is being broadcast
live on Facebook tonight

00:01:30.540 --> 00:01:34.650
by WBUR, and it will be
available in a few weeks

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:38.610
at Radcliffe.Harvard.edu.

00:01:38.610 --> 00:01:39.420
Good.

00:01:39.420 --> 00:01:41.730
So, before I
introduce the panel,

00:01:41.730 --> 00:01:44.659
I want to just say a couple of
words sort of how I ended up

00:01:44.659 --> 00:01:46.950
here, because it's sort of
related to what you guys are

00:01:46.950 --> 00:01:48.033
going to be talking about.

00:01:48.033 --> 00:01:51.540
So your moderator this evening,
who I'll introduce in a moment,

00:01:51.540 --> 00:01:54.630
is my colleague Shira
Springer, WBUR sports

00:01:54.630 --> 00:01:55.980
and society reporter.

00:01:55.980 --> 00:01:58.270
She asked me if I would
introduce this program,

00:01:58.270 --> 00:01:59.455
and I said, well, OK.

00:01:59.455 --> 00:02:00.330
And she said, no, no.

00:02:00.330 --> 00:02:01.038
You'd be perfect.

00:02:01.038 --> 00:02:03.030
You're a reporter.

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:05.520
You're a journalist,
and you're a fan.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.160
And I thought, does she
mean I'm a Red Sox fan?

00:02:08.160 --> 00:02:10.830
Because I'm kind of a
Red Sox fan, but I think

00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:12.870
I'm more of a Red Sox hostage.

00:02:12.870 --> 00:02:16.020
That's sort of the way
I think about that,

00:02:16.020 --> 00:02:18.090
and I want to explain that.

00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:20.340
And my story is
certainly not unique,

00:02:20.340 --> 00:02:26.920
but I had a grandfather who
was born sort of late 1800s.

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:29.440
He was passionate
about the Red Sox.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:33.120
He saw them win the
1918 World Series.

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:36.000
That's the last one he saw.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.700
And one of my
earliest memories is

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:42.240
my grandfather, who was
sort of a repressed Yankee

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:44.820
who didn't say a lot,
would come to the table,

00:02:44.820 --> 00:02:47.370
and just shake his
head, and say they

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:50.180
break your heart every day.

00:02:50.180 --> 00:02:52.130
This is one of my
earliest memories--

00:02:52.130 --> 00:02:56.090
that my dad, who
was born in 1918,

00:02:56.090 --> 00:03:00.150
the last time at that point that
they had won a World Series,

00:03:00.150 --> 00:03:05.520
spent his entire 82 years
waiting for a World Series

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:06.570
victory.

00:03:06.570 --> 00:03:09.750
Never saw one.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:12.180
Again, a lot of
us in this region

00:03:12.180 --> 00:03:14.190
have these stories to tell.

00:03:14.190 --> 00:03:15.940
We suffered.

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:17.480
It was painful.

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:22.772
And then came Pedro
Martinez and his fellow--

00:03:22.772 --> 00:03:27.910
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:27.910 --> 00:03:33.130
--and his fellow
idiots in 2004 when

00:03:33.130 --> 00:03:38.260
our entire world and really our
entire regional sports identity

00:03:38.260 --> 00:03:39.130
just changed.

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:41.710
It was just
overnight it changed.

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:43.510
I was telling Pedro
just before we

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:46.120
came up here I have a
21 year old daughter,

00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:47.547
and she's blase
about the Red Sox.

00:03:47.547 --> 00:03:48.880
It's like, dad, they always win.

00:03:48.880 --> 00:03:49.940
What's the big deal?

00:03:49.940 --> 00:03:53.188
It's like, how did this happen?

00:03:53.188 --> 00:03:56.260
Anyway, but here's the
point about tonight.

00:03:56.260 --> 00:03:59.050
So being a fan, or a hostage,
whatever you want to call it

00:03:59.050 --> 00:04:01.390
for all those years is
significant because it's not

00:04:01.390 --> 00:04:04.030
just about rooting
for your home team,

00:04:04.030 --> 00:04:05.770
because sometimes I didn't.

00:04:05.770 --> 00:04:08.050
Sometimes I got really
angry, and I just

00:04:08.050 --> 00:04:12.220
wanted them to lose quickly
so I could stop the pain,

00:04:12.220 --> 00:04:16.089
but this sort of unrequested
involvement with the Red Sox

00:04:16.089 --> 00:04:18.321
brought with it an
opportunity to think

00:04:18.321 --> 00:04:19.779
about a whole bunch
of other things

00:04:19.779 --> 00:04:21.347
that had nothing to
do with baseball.

00:04:21.347 --> 00:04:22.930
I mean, something
to do with baseball,

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:23.920
but not only baseball.

00:04:23.920 --> 00:04:29.030
Winning and losing, obviously,
but other more complicated

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:29.530
things.

00:04:29.530 --> 00:04:31.080
The way our country
has changed--

00:04:31.080 --> 00:04:33.610
in the Red Sox case, our
difficult relationship

00:04:33.610 --> 00:04:34.270
with race.

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:37.270
I mean just think about this
week and this whole debate

00:04:37.270 --> 00:04:40.270
about getting rid of
the name of Yawkey Way.

00:04:40.270 --> 00:04:44.350
So I'm grateful to have
this team in our midst

00:04:44.350 --> 00:04:47.350
for a lot of reasons,
including the richness

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:51.850
and complexity of issues that
sports can bring to the fore.

00:04:51.850 --> 00:04:54.340
And I'm just going to
tell very quickly one more

00:04:54.340 --> 00:04:59.500
story about the 2004 American
League Championship Series game

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:03.520
four at Fenway Park, which I
had the total honor of covering

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:05.140
for NPR.

00:05:05.140 --> 00:05:08.290
Now, you all know what
happened, but just in case

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:10.850
you don't, here's the
quick, quick synopsis.

00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:12.820
So the Red Sox were down
three games to nothing

00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:14.230
against the Yankees.

00:05:14.230 --> 00:05:17.620
Mariano Rivera is on
the mound, so it's over.

00:05:17.620 --> 00:05:20.560
The Red Sox are losing the
game, facing elimination,

00:05:20.560 --> 00:05:22.150
another disappointing season.

00:05:22.150 --> 00:05:23.810
Kevin Millar gets the base hit.

00:05:23.810 --> 00:05:25.390
Dave Roberts steals the base.

00:05:25.390 --> 00:05:27.040
Bill Miller gets the base hit.

00:05:27.040 --> 00:05:28.600
They tie it up.

00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:30.080
Extra innings.

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:32.950
Bottom of the 12th, David
Ortiz, winning home.

00:05:32.950 --> 00:05:34.900
They win game four.

00:05:34.900 --> 00:05:36.490
And you know what
happens after that.

00:05:36.490 --> 00:05:40.080
They win seven more games and
finally take the monkey off

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:41.590
of our backs.

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:45.910
My job was to cover that game,
and as a good NPR reporter,

00:05:45.910 --> 00:05:49.540
I wanted to get the sound
of the end of the game

00:05:49.540 --> 00:05:53.380
just in case it was
a Boston victory.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:05:55.204
I wanted the sound
of Fenway erupting.

00:05:55.204 --> 00:05:57.370
So bottom of the ninth
inning I go out in the stands

00:05:57.370 --> 00:05:59.650
with my microphone,
stand there, and wait.

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:00.400
Nothing happens.

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:02.710
Bottom of the 10th, stand
there, nothing happens.

00:06:02.710 --> 00:06:04.660
Bottom of the 11th,
nothing happens.

00:06:04.660 --> 00:06:07.000
Bottom of the 12th, I'm
there with my microphone

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.830
and up comes David Ortiz.

00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:12.100
Boom-- hits the home,
walk off home run.

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:13.750
Fenway comes to its feet.

00:06:13.750 --> 00:06:14.920
Huge cheer.

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:16.300
My microphone is going.

00:06:16.300 --> 00:06:18.060
Yes, I've got the sound.

00:06:18.060 --> 00:06:20.110
It's fantastic.

00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:24.200
So I go back to WBUR
to write my story,

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:25.960
and I start listening
to the tape,

00:06:25.960 --> 00:06:27.760
and I get to that
great moment where

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:30.970
I'm going to hear 37,000 people
cheering for the Red Sox.

00:06:30.970 --> 00:06:39.046
The only thing on that
tape is me screaming yeah!

00:06:39.046 --> 00:06:40.990
It's all that I could hear.

00:06:40.990 --> 00:06:41.962
So--

00:06:41.962 --> 00:06:46.822
[APPLAUSE]

00:06:46.822 --> 00:06:50.810
So that's the end of the story.

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:51.850
So Shira's right.

00:06:51.850 --> 00:06:52.540
I'm a fan.

00:06:52.540 --> 00:06:54.373
I was trying to be a
professional journalist

00:06:54.373 --> 00:06:56.620
that night, but I was a fan.

00:06:56.620 --> 00:07:00.490
So now it's my pleasure to
introduce this terrific panel.

00:07:00.490 --> 00:07:03.160
So ladies, gentlemen,
will you come up,

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:06.082
and I'll introduce you all.

00:07:06.082 --> 00:07:10.456
[APPLAUSE]

00:07:17.760 --> 00:07:21.690
To my immediate left, Shira
Springer, your moderator

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:23.790
tonight, who invited me here.

00:07:23.790 --> 00:07:26.700
So she's WBUR's sports and
society reporter covering

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:30.630
stories at the intersection
of sports and society,

00:07:30.630 --> 00:07:33.630
and before that, she wrote for
the Boston Globe as the Celtics

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:36.840
beat writer, then as an
investigative reporter

00:07:36.840 --> 00:07:38.280
and Olympic columnist.

00:07:38.280 --> 00:07:41.190
She grew up in Connecticut
cheering for the Hartford

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:44.250
Whalers and the New York Mets?

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:46.353
Come on, Shira.

00:07:46.353 --> 00:07:48.630
But-- hold on now--

00:07:48.630 --> 00:07:51.030
in high school, she saw
the error of her ways.

00:07:51.030 --> 00:07:53.520
She took down the pictures of
Keith Hernandez, and Darryl

00:07:53.520 --> 00:07:57.732
Strawberry, and Dwight Gooden,
and she became a Red Sox fan.

