has inspired everyone in
this room, but especially

01:44:31.800 --> 01:44:33.252
my students.

01:44:33.252 --> 01:44:34.860
- Thank you.

01:44:34.860 --> 01:44:37.710
- Back when I first
started, I had

01:44:37.710 --> 01:44:45.810
Tony Pena, who came to my
school, and the town lit up.

01:44:45.810 --> 01:44:49.760
I was a teacher in
Boston and also in Salem.

01:44:49.760 --> 01:44:53.350
But there are other people
who were predecessors--

01:44:53.350 --> 01:44:57.200
Mike Fornieles, Earl Wilson.

01:44:57.200 --> 01:44:59.900
If you study what
happened to Earl Wilson,

01:44:59.900 --> 01:45:04.640
the legacy is there that is so
sad, but we have in front of us

01:45:04.640 --> 01:45:10.930
someone who is celebrated
instead of denigrated.

01:45:10.930 --> 01:45:13.020
And that, to me, is
extremely important

01:45:13.020 --> 01:45:16.940
going through the years.

01:45:16.940 --> 01:45:20.380
If we looked at Reggie Smith,
if we looked at Elston Howard,

01:45:20.380 --> 01:45:22.994
I was there for the first
game for Pumpsie Green.

01:45:26.370 --> 01:45:28.800
My father had season tickets.

01:45:28.800 --> 01:45:31.490
Can you imagine, in the
'50s, season tickets?

01:45:31.490 --> 01:45:33.060
But we did.

01:45:33.060 --> 01:45:35.520
Jim Rice has stories--

01:45:35.520 --> 01:45:38.440
Reggie Smith.

01:45:38.440 --> 01:45:45.570
1967 in my life was the
most integrated team.

01:45:45.570 --> 01:45:47.790
That was the first
time that we-- gee,

01:45:47.790 --> 01:45:49.686
we were in the World Series.

01:45:53.060 --> 01:45:56.660
I also have to mention,
while I was in Boston

01:45:56.660 --> 01:45:58.850
was in the early '70s.

01:45:58.850 --> 01:46:07.086
My student was the first
black bat boy for the Red Sox.

01:46:07.086 --> 01:46:09.530
- And do you have a question?

01:46:09.530 --> 01:46:13.160
- My question is I wanted to
get all to the good stuff.

01:46:13.160 --> 01:46:16.400
Now I'm going to something else.

01:46:16.400 --> 01:46:17.390
Two things.

01:46:17.390 --> 01:46:21.130
When Pedro was pitching,
no one talked in our house.

01:46:21.130 --> 01:46:22.505
We only watched the game.

01:46:25.970 --> 01:46:30.160
But we have a problem here
in the United States right

01:46:30.160 --> 01:46:37.340
now with immigration, and I
see families being torn apart

01:46:37.340 --> 01:46:42.920
in my community, and I
want to know, as I look up

01:46:42.920 --> 01:46:45.130
here exploring sports
and citizenship,

01:46:45.130 --> 01:46:51.290
how the Red Sox can help with
our families being torn apart

01:46:51.290 --> 01:46:54.060
and deported?

01:46:54.060 --> 01:46:56.677
- We'll take another question,
and we'll kind of address--

01:46:56.677 --> 01:46:57.260
- [INAUDIBLE].

01:46:57.260 --> 01:46:59.290
- You sure you don't
want to handle that one?

01:46:59.290 --> 01:47:01.260
I don't want anyone to forget.

01:47:01.260 --> 01:47:02.920
- Sam, you said you can handle--

01:47:02.920 --> 01:47:05.740
- Well, why don't we-- in the
interest of keeping this--

01:47:05.740 --> 01:47:09.340
pace of the game is an
initiative for baseball

01:47:09.340 --> 01:47:10.390
these days.

01:47:10.390 --> 01:47:13.390
Just to quickly thank you
for sharing your memories

01:47:13.390 --> 01:47:15.500
and your question.

01:47:15.500 --> 01:47:20.290
We said it before, but Fenway
is a community gathering place,

01:47:20.290 --> 01:47:24.050
and it's a place that hopefully
people can come together.

01:47:24.050 --> 01:47:30.400
We've actually had immigration
ceremonies at Fenway Park.

01:47:30.400 --> 01:47:31.360
- Latino night.

01:47:31.360 --> 01:47:34.750
- We have Latino
night, Latino festival.

01:47:34.750 --> 01:47:39.010
We have Latino youth recognition
days each and every month.

01:47:39.010 --> 01:47:40.900
In fact, tonight was
one of those at Fenway.

01:47:40.900 --> 01:47:42.700
We missed it because
we were here,

01:47:42.700 --> 01:47:44.950
but I just think
Fenway is a place where

01:47:44.950 --> 01:47:47.680
we can all come
together and be one

01:47:47.680 --> 01:47:50.500
cheering for a common cause.

01:47:50.500 --> 01:47:52.720
When Pedro pitched, boy,
it was-- you're right.

01:47:52.720 --> 01:47:53.830
It was not a game.

01:47:53.830 --> 01:47:54.850
It was an event.

01:47:54.850 --> 01:47:58.630
So hopefully we can keep that
spirit going at Fenway Park.

01:47:58.630 --> 01:48:00.670
- And I'll just quickly
add that we also--

01:48:00.670 --> 01:48:03.340
our Red Sox Scholars
program can be

01:48:03.340 --> 01:48:05.410
given to undocumented students.

01:48:05.410 --> 01:48:09.040
And so in my past life, being
an ED for a nonprofit called

01:48:09.040 --> 01:48:11.052
Scholar Athletes, we
actually sought out

01:48:11.052 --> 01:48:12.760
undocumented students
because they're not

01:48:12.760 --> 01:48:14.320
eligible for federal aid.

01:48:14.320 --> 01:48:17.655
And so our dollars are critical
to help them pursue education.

01:48:17.655 --> 01:48:19.030
So that's yet
another way I think

01:48:19.030 --> 01:48:20.334
that we're really helping.

01:48:20.334 --> 01:48:21.250
- Can I add something?

01:48:21.250 --> 01:48:25.780
I'm just going to say something
on behalf of immigrants.

01:48:25.780 --> 01:48:29.140
The reason I'm here,
and celebrated, and not

01:48:29.140 --> 01:48:32.570
denigrated, like you
said, it was because I

01:48:32.570 --> 01:48:35.660
was granted an opportunity.

01:48:35.660 --> 01:48:38.640
So if in any way,
this panel is going

01:48:38.640 --> 01:48:43.060
to be useful for
this kind of matter,

01:48:43.060 --> 01:48:46.190
it's saying I don't
have a problem.

01:48:46.190 --> 01:48:49.890
We don't have a problem
with investigating

01:48:49.890 --> 01:48:53.890
who's the right fit or
maybe the right person

01:48:53.890 --> 01:48:58.555
to give an opportunity,
but please do it.

01:48:58.555 --> 01:48:59.930
You never know
where you're going

01:48:59.930 --> 01:49:02.460
to find another guy like me.

01:49:02.460 --> 01:49:03.660
[LAUGHTER]

01:49:03.660 --> 01:49:07.890
And you never know
what kind of human

01:49:07.890 --> 01:49:09.960
is going to be
helping another human.

01:49:09.960 --> 01:49:16.897
This gentleman over here asked
me who I probably influenced.

01:49:16.897 --> 01:49:19.230
I don't like to talk about
myself when it comes to that.

01:49:22.330 --> 01:49:26.640
This moment that I have
here that I can probably

01:49:26.640 --> 01:49:31.320
express myself and
express my feelings--

01:49:31.320 --> 01:49:33.540
those are the kind of things
that I would like to do.

01:49:33.540 --> 01:49:37.690
If anybody wants to be
influenced by what I'm saying,

01:49:37.690 --> 01:49:42.290
grant an immigrant that you
feel is right an opportunity.

01:49:42.290 --> 01:49:45.538
And the results
might be surprising.

01:49:45.538 --> 01:49:46.506
Give some opportunity.

01:49:46.506 --> 01:49:50.378
[APPLAUSE]

01:49:55.720 --> 01:49:57.520
- Hi, I'm Jim Solomon.

01:49:57.520 --> 01:50:00.570
I'm not a plant from
Shira, I promise,

01:50:00.570 --> 01:50:05.320
but I'm one of the owners of
the Harford Yard Goats, Colorado

01:50:05.320 --> 01:50:07.330
Rockies double-A team.

01:50:07.330 --> 01:50:13.270
And I want to first applaud
everything that the Boston Red

01:50:13.270 --> 01:50:15.790
Sox do for their community.

01:50:15.790 --> 01:50:20.260
It's noticed, and it's
truly appreciated.

01:50:20.260 --> 01:50:28.410
I'm wondering if you see
opportunities with regard to--

01:50:28.410 --> 01:50:32.850
well, you define this evening
as Red Sox nation, not just

01:50:32.850 --> 01:50:34.170
Boston Red Sox.

01:50:34.170 --> 01:50:39.180
And so I imagine that
includes Pawtucket, Portland,

01:50:39.180 --> 01:50:42.480
and the organization as
a whole, and that you

01:50:42.480 --> 01:50:46.830
have an interest in protecting
the brand vertically

01:50:46.830 --> 01:50:50.340
throughout the organization
and reaching out

01:50:50.340 --> 01:50:53.180
into the community
at all levels.

01:50:53.180 --> 01:50:57.450
And so what I want to know is
there are great cities like New

01:50:57.450 --> 01:50:58.050
Hampshire--

01:50:58.050 --> 01:51:01.840
Manchester for New
Hampshire Fisher Cats,

01:51:01.840 --> 01:51:05.785
Portland for the Sea Dogs,
and Hartford for the Yard

01:51:05.785 --> 01:51:09.420
Goats, but there are also a
number of minor league clubs

01:51:09.420 --> 01:51:12.870
that play in areas
that really need help

01:51:12.870 --> 01:51:14.740
even more than those cities.

01:51:14.740 --> 01:51:18.840
So what I want to know
is if you see opportunity

01:51:18.840 --> 01:51:22.650
for the big team,
the major league team

01:51:22.650 --> 01:51:26.100
to reach down to the
minor leagues, one,

01:51:26.100 --> 01:51:30.240
to encourage the ballplayers
to have more contact.

01:51:30.240 --> 01:51:37.480
Like the way you said Jackie
Bradley Jr. Talks to the kids

01:51:37.480 --> 01:51:40.860
doesn't really cost
money, but it's something

01:51:40.860 --> 01:51:44.850
that's really doable,
or the possibility

01:51:44.850 --> 01:51:47.350
of people in your minor
league organization,

01:51:47.350 --> 01:51:50.040
say, working with you on
community to get some more

01:51:50.040 --> 01:51:51.880
ideas of what they can do.

01:51:51.880 --> 01:51:53.700
So anyway, I want to know--

01:51:53.700 --> 01:51:56.520
and I don't know the experience
for a minor league player

01:51:56.520 --> 01:51:59.010
and how nervous
they are about just

01:51:59.010 --> 01:52:03.570
making the team, how
that affects their desire

01:52:03.570 --> 01:52:05.610
to get out and do anything
with the community.

01:52:05.610 --> 01:52:07.900
So I throw it out
there for anybody.

01:52:07.900 --> 01:52:09.900
- We're going to try to
do the two person thing.

01:52:09.900 --> 01:52:12.720
We have one more, I
think, question behind,

01:52:12.720 --> 01:52:14.560
so we'll get to some of that.

01:52:14.560 --> 01:52:15.510
Yes?

01:52:15.510 --> 01:52:17.940
- Hi, I'm Josh Coen, and
I'm in the eighth grade,

01:52:17.940 --> 01:52:20.276
and I'm a huge Red Sox fan,
so this is really cool.

01:52:20.276 --> 01:52:22.168
So, thank you.

01:52:22.168 --> 01:52:25.479
[APPLAUSE]

01:52:26.898 --> 01:52:30.140
So I just have a
pretty basic question.

01:52:30.140 --> 01:52:32.510
What is the biggest
change that pro athletes

01:52:32.510 --> 01:52:35.720
need to make in order to be
better role models for youth?

01:52:37.935 --> 01:52:40.435
- I'm guessing you're asking
this pro athlete, not this one.

01:52:40.435 --> 01:52:44.240
[LAUGHTER]

01:52:44.240 --> 01:52:48.260
- I think if you're
raised the proper way

01:52:48.260 --> 01:52:54.650
in every aspect I think
the change is not drastic.

01:52:54.650 --> 01:53:00.160
Just like I said before,
because of the way

01:53:00.160 --> 01:53:04.940
my upbringing was made me
strong in everything I did.

01:53:04.940 --> 01:53:08.410
And baseball is no
exception, and when

01:53:08.410 --> 01:53:11.770
you get to the big leagues
or you get anywhere,

01:53:11.770 --> 01:53:14.410
what you have to
do is stress what

01:53:14.410 --> 01:53:22.330
you learn before you got
there, execute, remain loyal.

01:53:22.330 --> 01:53:24.700
Like I said before,
you have to be

01:53:24.700 --> 01:53:29.800
consistent about what you did
to get you to where you are.

01:53:29.800 --> 01:53:32.090
You don't have to really go
through a dramatic change

01:53:32.090 --> 01:53:39.070
in things in order for you to be
from Pawtucket to the Red Sox.

01:53:39.070 --> 01:53:40.510
You just continue
to do the things

01:53:40.510 --> 01:53:44.170
that you were doing right
and do it with consistency.

01:53:44.170 --> 01:53:48.590
Same thing with your goals,
whatever they are in life,

01:53:48.590 --> 01:53:51.730
in baseball, sports, whatever.

01:53:51.730 --> 01:53:56.210
Just be consistent of
the things that you were

01:53:56.210 --> 01:53:58.800
taught before you got there.

01:53:58.800 --> 01:54:01.200
- That addressed those
questions in some way,

01:54:01.200 --> 01:54:03.520
and I think we're going to
have to wrap it up here.

